<div id=3D"kwmr-infobody"><h1 class=3D"eyTitle">Lumen to Watt Comparison</h=
1>
<div class=3D"resourceContent">
<div itemscope=3D"" itemtype=3D"http://schema.org/Question">
<meta itemprop=3D"name" content=3D"How do lumens work?">

<div itemprop=3D"suggestedAnswer" itemscope=3D"" itemtype=3D"http://schema.=
org/Answer">

<div itemprop=3D"text"><br><br>
<div style=3D"width: 90%; margin: auto; padding: 20px; background-color: #e=
bebeb;">
- =93How bright of a bulb do you need in that light fixture?=94<br>
<i>- =9360 watts.=94</i><br>
- =93Ok, got it.=94<br>
</div><br>
<br>
We=92ve all been part of a similar conversation before.  But there=92s a pr=
oblem with it: <b>It makes no sense at all.</b><br>
<br>
<h3>Measuring Brightness</h3><br>
It has become common and ingrained in our minds to think of how bright a li=
ght bulb or light fixture is based on its wattage.  A 60-watt bulb meant yo=
u got 60 watts of light.  That=92s how it=92s been for decades.  But watts =
are not a measure of light output.  Rather, they are a measure of how much =
energy a light source is consuming.<br>
<br>
What we=92re after here is brightness; the amount of light emitted by a lig=
ht source.  How bright is that light bulb or fixture?  How much light is it=
 giving off?  The unit of measurement to determine how much light a lamp or=
 luminaire emits is called  <b>lumens</b>.<br>
<br>
The lumen output is what determines brightness and is the term and measurem=
ent we should all start to get very familiar with.<br> =20
<br>
Older incandescent bulbs converted their used energy into visible light at =
a predictable rate (albeit terrible), so we were very familiar with it.  Bu=
t new LED technology is changing all that; requiring far less energy to giv=
e off the same amount of light.  And with LED technology constantly evolvin=
g and becoming more efficient, it is becoming more and more important that =
we become comfortable with lumens.<br>
<br><br><br>
<div id=3D"quote-section">
<a href=3D"https://www.takethreelighting.com/quote.html"><img src=3D"https:=
//sep.turbifycdn.com/ty/cdn/yhst-135552442550403/getquote-sm.jpg?t=3D175746=
7486&amp;" class=3D"quote-section"></a><h3>Get a Custom Quote</h3>
Contact us today and let us take the guesswork out of converting to LED!  W=
e'll assemble a custom quote for your project that meets your unique needs.
</div><br><br><h3>Comparing the Different Technologies</h3><br>
So how do these all stack up?  How many lumens did a traditional incandesce=
nt 60-watt light bulb give off?  What=92s the modern LED equivalent?<br>
<br>
Time for charts!<br>
<br>
<img src=3D"https://sep.turbifycdn.com/ty/cdn/yhst-135552442550403/lumen-co=
mparison-gen.jpg?t=3D1757467486&amp;" alt=3D"Lumen and wattage comparison o=
f common household bulbs for incandescent, HID, CFL, and LED lamps" style=
=3D"display: block;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto"><br>
<br>
This is just a general guide only, and limited to general purpose, househol=
d omnidirectional bulbs and their common brightness levels.  The efficiency=
 at which an LED converts the energy it is consuming into visible light (it=
s efficacy) is improving all the time, so its wattage usage will continue t=
o go down and down for the same amount of light output.<br>
<br>
<h3>Scaling Up</h3><br>
It is worth noting that as you scale up and start getting into larger bulbs=
 and light fixtures with more intense light output, additional factors come=
 into play when comparing different lighting technologies and you need to l=
ook beyond simply the lumen output.<br>
<br>
<b>Directionality</b> is one such factor.  This is increasing common in com=
mercial and industrial applications.  For example, suppose you have a parki=
ng lot light that uses a 250-watt metal halide HID lamp.  That 250-watt bul=
b outputs roughly 14,000 lumens (on average) in all directions.  But you do=
n=92t need the light in all directions; you only need the light down on the=
 surface of the ground.  With traditional lighting, a good percentage of li=
ght is lost before it hits the ground, often escaping into the fixture hous=
ing or diffusing as it bounces around the housing=92s reflectors.  The inte=
nsely powerful and energy-consuming HID lamp is needed in this case so that=
 enough of its light makes it down to the ground.<br>
<br>
Suppose you want to upgrade that same parking lot light fixture to LED.  Do=
es this mean you=92d need to find an LED area light that outputs the same 1=
4,000 lumens?  No, not necessarily.  Because LEDs are inherently directiona=
l, all of their light is pointed towards the target surface (in this case, =
the ground).  Depending on the situation, you might be able to use an LED f=
ixture that outputs only 7,000 or 10,000 lumens.<br> =20
<br>
There are many other factors that affect the light output of a fixture or b=
ulb, called Light Loss Factors.  These include ballast factor, ambient temp=
erature, voltage, optics, burnouts, lumen depreciation, and more.<br>
<br>
While it can get confusing at first to try and factor them all in to create=
 a true apples-to-apples comparison of high-output fixtures and lamps acros=
s different lighting technologies, the bottom line is that often <b>you wil=
l be able to use an LED that, on paper, has less lumen output than the trad=
itional light source</b>.  So not only will you save energy by simply switc=
hing to LEDs, you will likely be able to step down to a lower output fixtur=
e because of the increased optical efficiencies of LED fixtures, while main=
taining the same foot candle levels at the target surface.<br>=20
<br>
Naturally, this can vary greatly per project, depending on various conditio=
ns.  But as an overall guide, here are some common equivalents.  Note the d=
ifference in lumen outputs.<br>
<br>
<img src=3D"https://sep.turbifycdn.com/ty/cdn/yhst-135552442550403/lumen-co=
mparison-linear.jpg?t=3D1757467486&amp;" alt=3D"Lumen and wattage compariso=
n of linear fluorescent and LED tubes" style=3D"display: block;margin-left:=
 auto;margin-right: auto"><br>
<br>
<img src=3D"https://sep.turbifycdn.com/ty/cdn/yhst-135552442550403/lumen-co=
mparison-high-output.jpg?t=3D1757467486&amp;" alt=3D"Lumen and wattage comp=
arison of high output HID metal halide and LED bulbs and fixtures" style=3D=
"display: block;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto"><br>
